    "summary": "My pre-university education (VWO) was at Den Hulster in Venlo, and was bilingual, with half the classes in English instead of Dutch. I participated successfully in the Dutch Chemistry and Physics Olympiads and qualified for the final round in both, which were held simultaneously, so I had to choose one. I decided to participate in the Physics Olympiad and ultimately qualified as one of the 5 best students of the Netherlands, allowing me to participate in the International Physics Olympiad (IPhO) in Singapore.\n\nAfter finishing my VWO education cum laude in 2006, I studied Applied Physics at the Eindhoven University of Technology. I was awarded the propedeuse award, a price for the best first-year physics student. I obtained my Bachelor degree cum laude in 2009 after a project studying three-dimensionality in shallow vortices in the Turbulence and Vortex Dynamics group (WDY). After this, I immediately proceeded with my Master education, and in 2011 I graduated cum laude within the Coherence and Quantum Technology group (CQT) in a project to characterize the ion current produced by the Ultra Cold Ion Source.\n\nAfterwards I started a PhD project at the Molecular Biosensing for Medical Diagnostics group, also at Eindhoven University of Technology, studying the scattering properties of small chains of particles in a biosensor. I successfully defended my doctoral thesis \"Optical scattering of rotating dimers for biosensing applications\" on October 31st 2018.\n\nAt the moment I am orienting myself in order to find a job. I have broad scientific and technological interests, including computer science, physics, mathematics, and applications of these in biology and chemistry.",
